<p>Last week, the US House of Representatives advanced the MATCH Act — the Mandating Assessments of Chinese-procured Hardware Act. In plain English: <strong>Congress wants to lock chip equipment exports to China into law</strong>.</p>

<p>This isn't another round of sanctions escalation.</p>
<p>The rules of the game are changing.</p>

<h2>What Changed</h2>
<p>For the past three years, US chip restrictions relied on BIS administrative orders. The Commerce Secretary says "this can't be exported," and companies comply. That's an administrative action. A new Secretary could loosen it. A new administration could reverse it.</p>

<p>The MATCH Act shifts this power <strong>from the Commerce Department to Congress</strong>.</p>

<p>Translation: regardless of who sits in the White House in 2028, chip restrictions on China become <strong>codified law</strong>.</p>

<p>Tom's Hardware detailed the expanded scope: not just AI chips, but DUV lithography equipment (ASML's mainstream deep ultraviolet machines) now falls under the control list. The R Street Institute called it "Industrial Policy Dressed as National Security."</p>

<h2>Why It Matters</h2>
<p>If you're a decision-maker in a globalizing company, your strategy for the past three years was probably: "Wait it out. Eventually you'll be able to buy again."</p>

<p>With the MATCH Act, that assumption no longer holds. Because: <strong>executive orders can be changed. Laws cannot.</strong></p>

<p>BIS export controls have explicit "controlled item lists" — companies can build compliance programs around them. But once Congress codifies the restrictions, the list only grows. Look at the CHIPS Act — passed in 2022, and already amended twice with additional restrictions by 2025.</p>

<h2>Three Baselines to Reset</h2>
<p><strong>1. Supply chain planning</strong>: For chips, lithography equipment, and EDA software, assume restrictions will tighten over 5-10 years, not loosen. When building overseas factories, don't just look at labor costs — look at equipment procurement pathways.</p>

<p><strong>2. Compliance budget</strong>: Spending $500K on an export compliance team used to be "big company" behavior. It's becoming a standard operating cost. Micron is already lobbying Congress to tighten further — big companies will use controls to cement their moats.</p>

<p><strong>3. Technology roadmap</strong>: If the latest equipment is permanently off the table, can your product design "step back" to mature process nodes? This is what Huawei proved with the Mate 60 Pro — 7nm for a flagship chip isn't optimal, but it works.</p>

<h2>Bottom Line</h2>
<p>The MATCH Act is still in the legislative pipeline. But both R Street's critique and Lawfare's deep analysis converge on the same judgment: <strong>bipartisan containment of China's semiconductor sector is now Washington consensus</strong>.</p>

<p>Not whether — just how fast.</p>

